Melatonin
elatonin (-acetyl-5-methoxytryptamine) is a tryptophan metabolite, synthesized mainly by the pineal gland. elatonin has a number of physiological functions, including regulating circadian rhythms, clearing free radicals, improving immunity, and generally inhibiting the oxidation of biomolecules. elatonin receptors appear to be important in mechanisms of learning and memory in mice, and it can alter electrophysiological processes associated with memory, such as . t is generally accepted that melatonin deficit is closely related to aging and age-related diseases. ecreased levels of melatonin in serum and in  and the loss of melatonin diurnal rhythm are observed in patients with 
[53]. he first published evidence that melatonin may be useful in  was the demonstration that this neurohormone prevents neuronal death caused by exposure to the amyloid beta protein
[54]. elatonin also inhibits the aggregation of the amyloid beta protein into neurotoxic microaggregates. ecent report has indicated that melatonin can alter lipid levels of mitochondrial membranes induced by amyloid beta protein
[55]. elatonin has been shown to prevent the hyperphosphorylation of the tau protein in rats. tudies in rats suggest that melatonin may be effective for treating 
[56]. n  patients, melatonin supplementation has been suggested to improve circadian rhythmicity, and to produce beneficial effects on memory. xtensive clinical trials and studies with transgenic models are necessary to confirm the role of melatonin at the late pathological stage of .Melatonin
Melatonin (N-acetyl-5-methoxytryptamine) is a tryptophan metabolite, synthesized mainly by the pineal gland. Melatonin has a number of physiological functions, including regulating circadian rhythms, clearing free radicals, improving immunity, and generally inhibiting the oxidation of biomolecules. Melatonin receptors appear to be important in mechanisms of learning and memory in mice, and it can alter electrophysiological processes associated with memory, such as LTP. It is generally accepted that melatonin deficit is closely related to aging and age-related diseases. Decreased levels of melatonin in serum and in CSF and the loss of melatonin diurnal rhythm are observed in patients with AD
[53]. The first published evidence that melatonin may be useful in AD was the demonstration that this neurohormone prevents neuronal death caused by exposure to the amyloid beta protein
[54]. Melatonin also inhibits the aggregation of the amyloid beta protein into neurotoxic microaggregates. Recent report has indicated that melatonin can alter lipid levels of mitochondrial membranes induced by amyloid beta protein
[55]. Melatonin has been shown to prevent the hyperphosphorylation of the tau protein in rats. Studies in rats suggest that melatonin may be effective for treating AD
[56]. In AD patients, melatonin supplementation has been suggested to improve circadian rhythmicity, and to produce beneficial effects on memory. Extensive clinical trials and studies with transgenic models are necessary to confirm the role of melatonin at the late pathological stage of AD.
</sections.10>

